				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Nifty tricks for 65 LDoN. (Easy and hard)<a name="57329"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 18 04 12:11 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I'm not lvl 65 but I have done more than my fair share of LDoNs and I just wanted to throw in some words from experience.<br>
<br />
- A lot of folks don't realize that different songs have different radii of assist aggro on your target. Bellow has a large radius, while cancel magic has what I've seen to be the smallest, OoS an HoS seem to be somewhere in the middle. If you are having issues with proximity aggro from pulls you were sure you didn't need to lull on, try using another song to pull.<br>
<br />
- I think lulling is important, but I have also cut my pull times in half by using proximity to aggro without even lulling, just creep up, but remember that sometimes you need to give mobs a tick to aggro, be patient but efficient.<br>
<br />
- Someone already mentioned traps. I can't stress enough how important it is for us to be utilizing all of our abilities. This includes locating and disarming the multitudes of traps in most LDoNs, saving untold amounts of mana and time in the process with only a few clicks on your part. You'd be surprised.<br>
<br />
- The biggest problem with casters is the fact that they stand around when tagged and begin casting, there are two common ways to solve this problem:<br>
<br />
   1. Someone already mentioned, target, start the song then run around a corner. This works great but can cause issues in long hallways and such.<br>
<br />
   2. If you can, use your charm song. Target, charm, comman it to follow, then bring it back and break the charm, viola. This is obviously not as widely used but can be extremely helpful.<br>
<br />
- Something most of you already know but it hasn't been mentioned yet, our AE slows will not break mezzes. It can really help to throw a twist of this in while keeping 2-3 locked down, we all know that sometimes the smallest things make the biggest difference in EQ.<br>
<br />
- Most folks have thier own personal process for picking which mobs to lull and in what order, my only advice in this area is that you don't need to limit yourself to one at a time. Get in the habit of pulling 2-3 on normal and pairs on high risk. I have a ranger friend I always do LDoNs with and he peels away any unwanted mobs and roots them off in a corner when things get really hairy, this is so much easier than trying to do everything myself. It's ok, you don't have to do <b>everything</b> yourself!<br>
<br />

<br />
  Anyways, there's always more and I always forget something so I hope this helps and I'll probably have more to say later. LDoN was the best thing to happen to bards since FM, in my very humble opinion and it can really make or break you. It can be the perfect place to meet new friends so be open to new ideas and people, be positive and always take charge when you can. 
<br />
Happy pulling!!
<br />
 <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /> <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /> <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /></span></td>
